Text: Choosing the best birth control is a really personal decision. There are 18 different types to choose from and they each work differently. You have to use a condom every time you have sex, take the pill daily, get a new patch every week, change the ring every month, and the IUD or implant can last for years.

Text: The shot is a type of birth control that you get every 3 months to prevent pregnancy. It’s technically called DepoProvera and it works by preventing ovulation (when your body releases an egg) - no egg, no baby! If you don’t mind getting a quick prick every 3 months, you should definitely talk to your doctor about getting it.

Message JSON: {"userId":"5c2598a9-85fb-4f89-9883-651b13d3d862","text":"what does birth control do to ur body"}

Text: Changes in your period are a common side effect of birth control. But it’s usually a good thing! The pill, ring, and patch can get your period on track (no more surprises! 🙏🏽) and can make your period lighter, while others like the hormonal IUD, shot, and implant can stop your period completely. Sounds wild, but it's totally safe. The only birth control that can have a negative effect on your period is the copper IUD. It’s non-hormonal which is good for people who don’t want hormones but, it can make your period heavier.
